title: Congress races to avert a government shutdown, with Biden’s agenda in the balance.
content: The House and Senate are both expected to pass short-term bills to fund the government, but a planned infrastructure vote is in limbo amid deep party divisions.

title: Trump Super PAC Removes Corey Lewandowski After Sexual Harassment Claim
content: The move came after a donor to former President Donald J. Trump said that Mr. Lewandowski had made unwanted sexual advances and touched her inappropriately.

title: Panel Subpoenas 11 in Capitol Riot Inquiry, Eyeing Jan. 6 Rally Planners
content: The second round of subpoenas issued by the House select committee investigating the attack signaled that it was moving aggressively to go after crucial witnesses.

title: Activists take vaccine demands, and a mountain of fake bones, to the home of Biden’s chief of staff.
content: A small group of longtime AIDS activists sought to represent lives lost to what they see as the president’s failure to scale up vaccine manufacturing for global use.

title: Klete Keller, a 3-Time Olympian, Pleads Guilty in Capitol Riot Case
content: Keller, 39, faces a prison sentence of up to 20 years, but the first Capitol rioter to plead guilty to the same charge was sentenced to eight months.

title: Kyrsten Sinema Is at the Center of It All. Some Arizonans Wish She Weren’t.
content: The centrist senator is key to President Biden’s agenda in Washington. Her positions have angered some Democrats back home.

title: The world’s top central bankers see supply chain problems prolonging inflation.
content: The heads of the Federal Reserve, European Central Bank, Bank of England and Bank of Japan spoke on a joint panel Wednesday.

title: For Al Franken, a Comeback Attempt Goes Through Comedy Clubs
content: Onstage, the ex-senator and “S.N.L.” star doesn’t exactly address his fall from grace. But he doesn’t not address it either. Asked if he’ll run again, he is noncommittal.

title: Democrats Move to Avert Shutdown, but Divisions Imperil Biden’s Agenda
content: Democrats prepared a spending bill to keep the government funded past a Thursday deadline, but moderates dug in harder against their ambitious social safety net bill.

title: Kathy Hochul Aims to Raise $25 Million as Likely Rivals Eye Challenges
content: Governor Hochul hopes to raise the sum for her primary campaign next year, but her recent — and unexpected — ascension has left her little time to hit that goal.

title: Biden Struggles to Unite His Own Party Behind His Economic Agenda
content: The president canceled a trip to Chicago in an attempt to salvage a pair of bills containing trillions of dollars in spending on infrastructure, education, climate change and more.

title: What You Missed: Virginia Governor’s Debate
content: Former Gov. Terry McAuliffe, a Democrat, and Glenn Youngkin, a Republican, clashed Tuesday night. Here’s what to know.

title: Defense Chief Says He Advised Against Staying in Afghanistan ‘Forever’
content: Lloyd J. Austin III’s testimony before a House panel shed light on an apparent discrepancy about the advice President Biden said he had gotten from top military advisers.

title: How to Build a Paid Family Leave Plan That Doesn’t Backfire
content: Congress is designing a policy as part of Democrats’ safety net spending plan. Evidence from around the world suggests what works and what doesn’t.

title: Republicans at Odds Over Infrastructure Bill as Vote Approaches
content: With a bipartisan infrastructure bill set for a Thursday vote in the House, a campaign by business groups and some Senate Republicans to secure G.O.P. support may be the measure’s last hope.

title: ‘This Was a Failure’: Biden’s A.T.F. Pick Says White House Left Him Open to Attack
content: David Chipman’s defeat was a loss for gun control groups, which saw the appointment of a strong director as the most important move the president could make on guns.

title: Military Officials Say They Urged Biden Against Afghanistan Withdrawal
content: During a heated Senate hearing, Gen. Mark Milley also defended his actions in the final months of the Trump administration.

title: How the Huawei Case Raised Fears of ‘Hostage Diplomacy’ by China
content: Critics of the Justice Department deal to free the Huawei executive Meng Wanzhou say it could blunt tools like sanctions and prosecutions.

title: Pfizer and BioNTech Submit Data Backing Vaccine for Children 5 to 11
content: The companies said that their vaccine was safe and effective in that age group, and that they would submit a formal request in the coming weeks to U.S. regulators to allow a pediatric dose.

title: How the Debt Ceiling Came to Be a Political Cudgel
content: The current fight over raising the debt limit is proving to be another lesson in American political dysfunction.

title: Navient, with six million borrowers, asks to stop servicing federal student loans.
content: Navient is the second major federal student loan servicer to ask to get out of the business. FedLoan said in July that it wanted out.
